{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608671/1957123101/0970.xml":{"full_text":"B-10\nTHE EVENING STAR\nWashington, D. C\nWWMI. wcntm at. I SOT\nCONTRACT\nBRIDGE\nBy EASLEY BLACKWOOD\nIt may come u something\nlem than a bombshell of Infor\nmation when I announce that\nbridge players are not noted\nfor their modesty. One bold\nclaim you hear now and then\nla \"opponents' overtoils dont\nbother os. We go right ahead\nand reach our right spot any\nway\"\nNorth dealer.\nNorth-South vulnerable.\nNORTH\n(Md. Abel)\n*O3\nJ 75\nP AKQt7\n*K\u00abJ\nWEST EAST\n(Mr. Dale) (Miss Brash)\n*lOl6 4 A J 9 7\n<?Q96S U1\n*6433 10\n*6 *QJ 106 33\n80UTH\n(Mrs. Keen)\n*K33\nV Ald\u00ab3\nJ 65\nA7 6\nThe bidding:\nNorth East South West\n1* 3* 30 All pass\nOpening lead: Queen of clubs.\nDon\u2019t believe a word of It.\nOvercalls can and do cause\nconfusion and Indecision even\nIn the most select bridge circles.\nThe most deadly ot all over\nealls is the one which uses up a\nmaximum of bidding space. An\novercall of one heart over a one\ndiamond opening uses up no\nbidding at all. Third hand can\nconveniently bid one spade or\ntwo clubs or whatever he\nplanned to bid. And. it he had\nplanned to respond with one\nheart, he can merely double.'\nA two-club overcall over sn\nopening diamond bid is a dif\nferent proposition. Here the\nresponder has been deprived of\nthe opportunity of bidding one\nheart, one spade or one no\ntrump.\nIn today's deal If Miss Brash\nhad stayed out of the auction\nMrs Keen would have had no\nproblem. Her hand was strong\nenough to make two forward\ngoing bids without definitely\ncommitting the hand to a game\ncontract. Her first bid would\nhave been one heart.\nIf her partner then bid one\nno-trump or two diamonds she\nwould have bid two no-trump\nwith a feeling that she had now\ndone full justice to her holding.\nAnd on that sequence of bid\nding Mr. Abel, with well over a\nminimum opening, would have\nbeen happy to go to three no\ntrump. v\nBut after the overcall Mrs\nKeen was in a bad spot. A bid\nof two no-trump would commit\nher side to game\u2014a commit\nment she was not strong\nenough to assume. A two\nheart bid would do just about\nthe same thing. A penalty\ndouble might be the best bet\u2014\nbut again it might not Mrs\nKeen had to guess and she\nfinally settled on a two-dia\nmond call as the least of the\nevils.\nNow Mr. Abel also had prob\nlems. His possible reblds were\nthree diamonds, two no-trump\nor pass. With no sure stopper\nIn either major suit he decided\nto pass.\nHere the story should end.\nAnd. to make my point about\nthe effect of overcalls on op\nponents\u2019 bidding. I showed the\nauction closing at a two-dia\nmond contract.\nWhen the hand was actually\nplayed Miss Brash could not let\nwell enough alone. She re\nopened the bidding with two\nspades and this gave Mrs. Keen\na chance to show her previously\nundisclosed strength with a bid\nof two no-trump. Mr. Abel car\nried on to three, which was\nmade without difficulty.\n(DOtribuUtf bv McNausht Syndic*'#\nLAW IN THE NEWS\nLawyers Pictured\nAs Keeping Peace\nBy PHIL YEAGER\nand JOHN STARK\n\"The first thing we do, let\u2019s\nkill ell the lawyers.\"\u2014Henry VI.\nNew Year\u2019s Is a time for\nresolutions, and It's hard to\ndeny that a lot of {oiks would\nbe Inclined to go along with\nDick the Butcher In the above\nsuggestion as a good way to\nbegin 1958.\nFor lawyers are often reputed\nto be argumentative, picayune,\nredundant and enchanted with\nthe sound of their voices or the\ngenius of their Ideas. More\nover. they are pictured as In\ncessantly promoting new rules\nand regulations, stirring up,\ntrouble and creating all kinds\nof business for themselves.\nRegulations Multiply\nLook at all the exasperation\nand frustration abroad in to\nday\u2019s world\u20149o percent of It\ncreated by rules, rules, rules.\nTake Harry B. Solomon, a\nbusinessman from Silver Spring.\nMd.. who got tagged by Mary\nland police for buying too much\nChristmas cheer In the District i\nof Columbia and driving home\nwith It. Not that Maryland Is\n\"dry.\u201d but liquor la cheaper In\nneighboring Washington, so the\nFree State has a law which\nkeeps folks from taking more\nthan two quarts a month home\nwith them.\nTake the Purdue University\ncoeds who have recently been\nordered by their dormitory\nsuperintendents to limit good-\nCROSSWORD PUZZLE\nACROSS (Answer to Yesterday's Tussle) 11 Orim weapon\n1 Tobacco kiln inn insiiii miiiii iii r i BalUeport\n5 Major Allan- ?*1? Ag E II? 13 Cubic meter\ntic port in TOWMiI 0 Kl| [t lS Iroquotan\nAfrica WflaWil&tSiU lndUn\n10 Meat prod- Tilllnff 21 Not working\nucu ml It Dll ISM I|L Y A 25 Domestic\n14 Motor UrviAM T| I|ETL| pets: 2 words\n15Qrenoble's I^iETnlCi 11 LIEIRMIBjTTOINIDIEI 24City in Alaa\nriver j I]LPTBIEIainBBBB ka. pop. 1,876\n16 Instigate ISI >l6l llttl sMeBiIIaiTTVIBIUIS I 37 Island off\n17 Herr's wife [U [LtE ml AMBBTotolklEll\u00df AIP IT I Tuscany\n18 Achieve a ft] siTl\nsignificant iTcTillfol ufO SBOI*INIA El 39 Yale men\neffect: 2 wds. [Nflllrn'TlWTCmSiVlgtilTTlTFl 30 Rodent\n30Broadway IMTITIitItBIeIMIAII TIEIS Cl 31 Appeared\ncomedy of iMillSiSiklVt'i\u00dfstflttll\u00dflflvl 33 Dies\u2014: Latin\n1953: 3 wds. >Xi,lAiil.\u00abaJ 1. 1 I*l I Judmsnt Day\na Mai de 33 Much-used\n33 Well-known 41 Carved gem 63 The Bled \"schoolbook\"\nmonogram of the jabot Piper\u2019s river 34 Streets: Abbr.\n34Qulct>wUted *\u00bba 68 Shore bird S 6 Bests on\n36 Senator I torn *\u00bbOWN\n\u2022Hfc I SS i\nStott 3 Distinctive 39 Malayan dyed\n30 He married 48\nPocahaitsi reading I Knife thrust 40 Regal woman\n#1 47 Insect 4 A feat of in- 42Tothtok: Fr.\n11 48 Water off genulty:S 43 Senor Casals\nIndia words 44 Premier Chou\n85 Lists to avoid Walt of 45 Place for a\n57 Former Met. Hollywood horse\n36 \u2018tar 6 Thin Man's 49 Ten cents\nuseoiornne M Surprised ex- dog 50 Osiris'wife\nciotn clamatlon 7 Notch made 51 Salt tree\n37 See 33 Down sgWhatamias by ax or saw 52 Man's name\n1,1 Is aa good as: I Diva's forte 53 Jewish month\nP. D. Arsenal: 2 words 9 Light up 54 The Darlings'\n3 words 10 smuggler's again baby sitter\n40 Teen-agers nemesis llSoundof 56 Coral reef off\nblue 61 Too smooth triumph a mainland\nr\u2014ti e p hh r* p j* p\u2019THrTTrrTr\" is\nmr I\nI ll zjz r\njo\niO St 52 W\nI\nj\nHow tO\nSTOP KILLING i\n%L YOURSELF\nr I ly D PETER J STE,NCROHN\nRecovery Room Care Saves Lives\nDear Dr. ftteineroha: I\nwonder hew many es year\nreaders knew es the existence\nes sack a glare la meet mod\nern hospitals aa the recovery\nRoom. 1 think they should\nknow for two reasons. The\nfirst is that many a patient's\nlife has been saved by the\nattention received there. And\nsecond, it will save nanny anx\nious relatives needless anx\niety and heartache waiting\nfor hoars In the patient's\nroom wondering why the\noperation is taking so long.\nFor example, my husband\nwas operated an for his gall\nbladder a few weeks ago. I\nwaited in his room for six\nhours\u2014all the while think\ning something had gone\nwrong on the operating room\ntable. Then I was told that\nhe was all right\u2014that he\nwas being observed in the\nrecovery room with all the\nother patients who had been\noperated on that morning.\nAnd I also learned later that\nhe might have died if he\nhadn\u2019t been la that room.\nHe suddenly stopped breath\ning about an hour after they\nbrought him to the recovery\nroom. Only the rloae ob\nservation of the nurse, and\nhaving the proper Instru\nments and a doctor Immedi\nately on hand, saved his life.\nDe you wonder why I am en\nthused about the recovery\nroom and want people to\nknow about It? Mrs. S. 11. J.\nWhen I was an Intern the\nmight kisses to one\u2014and make\nthat one snappy with \"little or\nno emotion.\u201d Handshakes are\nrecommended.\nOr take the big league base\nball clubowners who decided\nthe other day to teleca* a few\nSunday games on coast-to\ncoast networks next year. They\nhave been bombarded with\nthreats of antitrust proceed\nings. Congressional Investiga\ntions court challenges and\nInjunctions.\nAlternative Is Mayhem\nLaws and rules and regula\ntions everywhere you turn!\ni And It Is that \"lawyer com\nplex\" bringing them all ont\nI Or Is It?\nMaybe it Is more because this\nglobe Is shrinking so fast and\nthe population la growing so\nfast that everybody la getting\nIn everybody rise's hair. It Is\nmighty hard these days to do\nanything that doesn't directly\naffect others, or at least the\ninterests of others. And when\nthat happens you have to have\nrules or mayhem, one or the\nII other.\nThus the Hartford Courant\nput It kindly on behalf of bar\nrlaters not long ago. \"Lawyers\naren't such bad chaps, really,\"\nIt editorialised. \"They only seek\nto reduce to the printed word\nand decision a means of getting\nalong, whether In contracts,\nJ crime or corrections.\"\nr FriJsy: Failure H Jim headlights |i\n'lrisk f butintii. t\nI patient just operated upon \u00abu\nwheeled back to his room in i\ncharge of a nurse\u2014often an in-\nexperienced student nurae. She\nwould be Instructed to support t\nthe angle of hia jaw so that i\nbreathing would not be im- i\npeded. If there was nausea or\nvomiting she helped the patient\nthrough that uncomfortable\nphase of his poet \u2022operative ex* i\nperience.\nShe took his pulse and ob- t\nserved hia \"color.\" If after an\nhour or so the patient seemed j\nto be resting normally, the\nnurse would go about her other\nduties and peek in once in\nawhile to see that everything\nwas all right.\nAnd usually it was. But i\nthere were enough exceptions t\nthat medical men over the year\nawakened to the need for closer\nscrutiny of the patient who had j\njust been submitted to major\nsurgery and deep anesthesia.\nPreventlble post-o perat iv e,\ndeath is not excusable.\nThe modern recovery room i\nsetup is organized with the real-\nnation that the patient is prob-\nably in less danger while on the\noperating table than during the j\nfirst hour or two after the op-j\neration. It is during this period 1\nthat there is greater danger of\nj hemorrhage, shock or obstruc\ntion to breathing. 1\nIn the patient's own room or\nward, observation is of neces-\nsity sporadic. The nurae can't\nbe in two places at once. She\nmay be out of the room for 10\nor IS minutes getting some\nthing for the patient. During\nthat time he may choke on I\nsome phlegm and cease breath\ning.\nSuch an accident rarely, if\never, happens in the recovery\nroom. Every patient is under\nconstant watch until his dis\ncharge to his own room. If a\ndoctor is quickly needed, he is\nimmediately available because\nthe recovery room is adjacent\nr to the operating rooms.\nAnd all the \u201ctools\u201d are there 1\nfor the asking: Blood trans\nfusion: plasma: stimulants:\noxygen: electrocardiographs;\ni laryngoscopes and broncho\nscopes; even a small chest-set 1\nr for \u2018\u2018going in'* to massage a\ni heart that has stopped beating\nWe rarely think of it as such.\nbut I consider the modem re- 1\n1 covery room as one of the\ngreater advances of surgery\nduring the past quarter cen\ntury.\ni\u00dfmmmS b\u00bb Tht Sell Srndirttt. Inc\nTomorrow: PotttWt COOMI of tod\nenrol tor log crompt oro diKuuod\nLife's Like That\n\u201cI think It', tlllr u ten*,\nthe party just because you\nJ couldn\u2019t And a hat you\nI liked\nn\nT| 888 f MviCIV _\u2019\\ttpfl p j Wy\u00ae'^\n7 v mimM\u00dft Ik\n[l'rtM Jj I! r KfT*\\k jjnj |pf| IVVV>rf|y^i\nj ft\u00abj(a I 1 BBMm Mf/Uwu l/T Jjr mk\nW6RDS, WIT\nAND WISDOM\nBy WILLIAM MORRIS\nPittsburgh. Pa.: Ploaao let\nme know why they are called\n\"Harvard beets Are they col\nlege beets?\u2014Eugene R. Aprea.\nAnswer: A half century or so\nago. when Harvard had some\nof the finest football teams In\nthe country. Harvard crimson\nwas a color known throughout\nthe land. About that time a\nchef, whose name unfortunate\nly has been lost to history, con\nfected a dish of cooked beets\nwarmed in a sauce of vinegar,\nsugar and cornstarch, whose re\nsulting deep red color was very\nclose to the crimson in Har\nvard's then proud banners. Eu\nreka An inspiration\u2014and the\nname of \u201cHarvard beets\u201d was\ncoined.\nNew York, N. Y.: It seems to\nme that I once heard that two\nof the most common men\u2019s\nouter garments were named for\na pair of British officers in the\nCrimean War. Can you fill me\nin on this?\u2014W. J. Miller.\nAnswer: The Earl of Cardi\ngan gave his name to the knit-,\nted woolen, front-buttoning\nsweater. The Earl of Raglan's\nfame in men's wear circles\nhangs upon his invention of\nthe raglan overcoat, in which\nthe sleeves continue in one\npiece to the collar, without the,\nshoulder seam found in other\noutercoats.\nIt's ironic tliat their fame\nshould now rest on such home\nly articles, for in their lifetimes\nthey were among the most cel\nebrated\u2014and bumbleheaded\u2014\nof military leaders. It was Car\ni digan who led the doomed\nmarch of the Light Brigade at\nBalaclava in the Crimea, while\nRaglan was in supreme com\nmand of the British forces dur\ning that war. Though praised\nby Victoria for his services, he\nwas sharply criticized by mili\ntary experts for his handling\nof the campaign. The story is\nsuperbly told, by the way. in\nCecil Woodham-Smlth's book\n'The Reason Why,\u201d one of the\nfinest historical narratives of\nour time.\n(Bill Srndlcalt)\nFAMOUS FABLES\nBy E. E. EDGAR\nPATRONAGE: President\nWoodrow Wilson, always the\nscholar, had a profound dis\ntaste for routine politics and\npoliticians. He especially dts-j\nliked patronage, although he\naccepted it as a necessary evil.\nWhen elected Oovemor of\nNew Jersey he refused to see\nparty workers seeking Job ap\npointments. Instead he had\nhis secretary draw up a list of\nnames, from which he made his\nelections. As a result Wilson\nrarely met the people he ap\npointed.\nOne day. as he and his sec\nretary were emerging from the\nexecutive mansion, a man\nrushed up to him and began\nshaking his hand vigorously.\n\u201cThank you, Mr. Oovernor,\nthank you,\" he cried, gratitude\nwritten on his face. \u201cMl never\nforget It!\u201d\nWilson stared at the man lnj\nbewilderment. When the other\n!had departed, he turned to his\nsecretary and asked:\n\u201cWhat did I do for him?\u201d\nWORD GAME\nFind 38 or more words in\nRUBEOLA\nmeaning, \u201cthe measles.\u201d Aver\nage Is 36; time limit, 3B min\nutes.\nRults sf tht ttmt \u20141 Words mutt\nI be of four or morr ItUrrt 2. Wordit\nwhich acoiilrt four luttcrt hr the addi\ntion of tur.li at 'bolt, \u201ctort.\u201d art\nj nol uttd S Onlr onr form of a word\nIt uttd. 4 Proper ntmtt art not uttd\nSotwtr to PACTION\nfttt. film ftln Sit font. fori, action,\nantic. Mill, atonic, canto cant, coin\ncoat, tolf, tonic, man. Into. lota, atit\n\nDAVID CRANlrj^Jpp| I \u00abow ymy os\u00ab, thsv arc Twvourr mi mty imjm row\nit jj&M nan An )zv \u00abi mo i sap you* \u00abwa the oensnu*\n|Lm TALKING. #O'..THSYDCKTUNDH\\ if R VICf, AND OA COURSE THAT\nOKtrr taotsney ootrrwtcy\nj\nTHI POTTS p \u20147 r\n__ amd \u00a94O \\oPCDu\u00abt J tsrvFe wo\u00bb*y y\n*USTNKSuTIWADADeeA* \"V 1 \u00a9O-DBAC J MOCN *ONSV\nTHAT I SAW A LOVELY PuCCOAT IT T 1 I\n\u2014\u2014...0;\u2014 1 J\nIAILIY I /lunch- 1 ftOOP WHEW.'\n___{ TIMS, 1 N**t, (WHATA w.\n1 I .y.\u2014 I\nTHE JACKSON TWINS f OH/weu~(swh) Y wey, \\clsc scr just 'i up s, ups, ups/ jaa I name\nH WE WERE BkS PXI MATE HIS RESOLUTION, VOU WOULP MA/E A STRANGE 1\nA WHILE/ WE HAP) TWINS HE'S PJVPLOCUN' TO WAVE TWO /PEEUNG TVKY\n\u2014tv sir PKe l 'Ss?\u00a3? k\nI\u2019vt BEEkJ NOuft PAL TINA TO BLOW aooo Mine a nl-rc IP THESE. Vi\nWMTiNB ItApATIfNTDf KM X\u2122E OLD MEAC J WAS A C Y\n2n\u00bbS?IS\u00ab\u2014","height":"28583","width":"18275"}}
